Section 6.2 (Edition 8, pg 426-427)


6.2.1

The six meetings (pigeons) are placed in five days (boxes). By the Pigeonhole Principle (PP) one of the days must contain two or more meetings. In other words, there exist some weekday where at least two classes have regular meetings.

6.2.3

a) If he takes out three socks then at least two of them must be of the same color. This follows from the PP.
b) In the worst case, the first 12 socks he takes out are brown. Therefore, he has to take out 14 socks to be sure there is at least two black socks.

6.2.8

There are dddd possible remainders (0,1,2,\ldots,d-10,1,2,…,d−10,1,2,\ldots,d-10,1,2,…,d−1) when dividing an integer by dddd. Think of these remainders as our boxes. Out pigeons are the d+1d+1d+1d+1 integers. Hence, by the PP, at least two of the d+1d+1d+1d+1 integers leaves the same remainder when divided by dddd.

6.2.12

Let (x_i, y_i)(xi,yi)(x_i, y_i)(xi​,yi​) and (x_j, y_j)(xj,yj)(x_j, y_j)(xj​,yj​) be two different point from our set of five points.

Now, the middle point on the line segmnet joining these two points has coordinates \left(\frac{x_i+x_j}{2}, \frac{y_i+y_j}{2}\right)(xi+xj2,yi+yj2)\left(\frac{x_i+x_j}{2}, \frac{y_i+y_j}{2}\right)(2xi​+xj​​,2yi​+yj​​). When are both these coordinates integers? They are integers exactly when x_i+x_jxi+xjx_i+x_jxi​+xj​ and y_i+y_jyi+yjy_i+y_jyi​+yj​ are divisible by 2222. Or in other words, when x_i+x_jxi+xjx_i+x_jxi​+xj​ and y_i+y_jyi+yjy_i+y_jyi​+yj​ are even numbers.

The sum of two integers is even if and only if they are both even, or they are both odd.

Let us consider all possible combinations of even and odd numbers (parities) for a point with integer coordinates in the plane (2 dimensions):

(\text{odd}, \text{odd})\\
(\text{odd}, \text{even})\\
(\text{even}, \text{odd})\\
(\text{even}, \text{even})
(odd,odd)(odd,even)(even,odd)(even,even)(\text{odd}, \text{odd})\\ (\text{odd}, \text{even})\\ (\text{even}, \text{odd})\\ (\text{even}, \text{even}) (odd,odd)(odd,even)(even,odd)(even,even)

So each of our points fall into one of these four cases. Since we have five points, and there are only four possible cases, one of them must be the case for at least two of our points. This follows from the PP.

This completes the proof. Do you see why?

6.4.36

Let P(n)P(n)P(n)P(n) be the proposition (x+y)^n=\sum_{j=0}^n\binom{n}{j}x^{n-j}y^j(x+y)n=∑j=0n(nj)xn−jyj(x+y)^n=\sum_{j=0}^n\binom{n}{j}x^{n-j}y^j(x+y)n=∑j=0n​(jn​)xn−jyj. We want to prove, using induction, that \forall n\geq0 P(n)∀n≥0P(n)\forall n\geq0 P(n)∀n≥0P(n).

Base case: When n=0n=0n=0n=0, we have (x+y)^0=1(x+y)0=1(x+y)^0=1(x+y)0=1 and \sum_{j=0}^0\binom{0}{j}x^{0-j}y^j=\binom{0}{0}x^0y^0=1∑j=00(0j)x0−jyj=(00)x0y0=1\sum_{j=0}^0\binom{0}{j}x^{0-j}y^j=\binom{0}{0}x^0y^0=1∑j=00​(j0​)x0−jyj=(00​)x0y0=1 and hence P(0)P(0)P(0)P(0) is true.

Induction hypothesis: Assume that P(m)P(m)P(m)P(m) is true for some m\geq 0m≥0m\geq 0m≥0. That is, the following equality holds: (x+y)^m=\sum_{j=0}^m\binom{m}{j}x^{m-j}y^j(x+y)m=∑j=0m(mj)xm−jyj(x+y)^m=\sum_{j=0}^m\binom{m}{j}x^{m-j}y^j(x+y)m=∑j=0m​(jm​)xm−jyj.

Induction step: We want to show that P(m)\implies P(m+1)P(m)  ⟹  P(m+1)P(m)\implies P(m+1)P(m)⟹P(m+1). Now,

\begin{align*}
(x+y)^{m+1} &= (x+y)(x+y)^m = (x+y)\sum_{j=0}^m\binom{m}{j}x^{m-j}y^j\\
&=x\sum_{j=0}^m\binom{m}{j}x^{m-j}y^j+y\sum_{j=0}^m\binom{m}{j}x^{m-j}y^j\\
&= x\left(\binom{m}{0}x^m+\sum_{j=1}^m\binom{m}{j}x^{m-j}y^j \right) + y\left(\sum_{j=0}^{m-1}\binom{m}{j}x^{m-j}y^j + \binom{m}{m}y^m\right)\\
&= x^{m+1} + \sum_{j=1}^m\binom{m}{j}x^{m-j+1}y^j + \sum_{j=0}^{m-1}\binom{m}{j}x^{m-j}y^{j+1} + y^{m+1}\\
&= x^{m+1} + \sum_{j=1}^m\binom{m}{j}x^{m-j+1}y^j + \sum_{j=1}^{m}\binom{m}{j-1}x^{m-j+1}y^{j} + y^{m+1}\\
&= x^{m+1} + \sum_{j=1}^m\left(\binom{m}{j}+\binom{m}{j-1}\right)x^{m-j+1}y^{j} + y^{m+1}\\
&= x^{m+1} + \sum_{j=1}^m\binom{m+1}{j}x^{m-j+1}y^{j} + y^{m+1}\\
&= \sum_{j=0}^{m+1}\binom{m+1}{j}x^{m+1-j}y^j.
\end{align*}

6.4.37

a) To get from (0,0)(0,0)(0,0)(0,0) to (m,n)(m,n)(m,n)(m,n) we need to perform exaclty mmmm steps to the right and nnnn steps upwards. In total, we need to perform m+nm+nm+nm+n steps. So each path can be naturally represented by a binary strings consisting of mmmm zeros and nnnn ones. For example, if we read left to right, we can represent the first example path by the binary string 01100010011000100110001001100010 and the second example path by 10000011100000111000001110000011.

b) There are \binom{m+n}{n}(m+nn)\binom{m+n}{n}(nm+n​) such binary strings (of length n+mn+mn+mn+m digits with nnnn ones). Hence, there are \binom{m+n}{n}(m+nn)\binom{m+n}{n}(nm+n​) paths of the dersired type.
